{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477677"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:03:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14678"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14678"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.22,0.17,0.06,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7371"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70438"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1224"},{"type":"tags","id":"3617"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44216"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for routine immunisations. He has severe atopic dermatitis requiring daily topical corticosteroids and moisturiser. He recently developed egg allergy confirmed by skin prick testing. He is exclusively breastfed and growing appropriately. He has no other medical conditions and takes no regular medications apart from his skin treatments. His parent enquires about introducing solid foods and preventing food allergies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allergy testing before supervised peanut introduction","Commence peanut-containing foods at 12 months","Begin regular peanut consumption immediately","Postpone peanut introduction until age three","Recommend lifelong peanut avoidance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant has two major risk factors for peanut allergy development: severe atopic dermatitis and confirmed egg allergy. Research has demonstrated that early introduction of peanut-containing foods can prevent peanut allergy in high-risk infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergy testing before supervised peanut introduction\u003C/strong\u003E represents best practice for infants with severe atopic dermatitis or egg allergy. This involves skin prick testing or specific IgE measurement to assess sensitisation status. The results guide whether introduction should occur under medical supervision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeginning regular peanut consumption immediately\u003C/strong\u003E without prior testing could be dangerous in this high-risk infant who may already be sensitised to peanut protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostponing peanut introduction until age three\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts current evidence. Research shows that delayed introduction increases allergy risk rather than preventing it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending lifelong peanut avoidance\u003C/strong\u003E is outdated advice that has been shown to increase allergy risk. The current approach emphasises controlled early exposure rather than avoidance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing peanut-containing foods at 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E misses the critical window for optimal introduction. Guidelines now recommend introduction between 4-11 months after appropriate risk assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis represents a significant shift in allergy prevention strategy, moving from allergen avoidance to carefully managed early introduction. Clinical trials have demonstrated up to 80% reduction in peanut allergy when high-risk infants receive early, appropriate exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Early peanut introduction (4-11 months) significantly reduces peanut allergy risk in high-risk infants.","Severe eczema and egg allergy are key risk factors requiring allergy testing before peanut introduction.","Supervised medical introduction of peanut is essential in high-risk infants after allergy testing."],"references":["Elghoudi A, Narchi H. Food allergy in children-the current status and the way forward. World J Clin Pediatr. 2022 May 9;11(3):253-269. doi: 10.5409/wjcp.v11.i3.253. PMID: 35663006; PMCID: PMC9134150."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70438"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14678"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70438"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-19T17:37:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-19T17:38:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7371"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86169"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i